# =============================================================================
# LOCK FILES - DECISION POINT
# =============================================================================
# Lock files ensure reproducible builds (same dependencies everywhere)
#
# RECOMMENDATION: Commit lock files for:
#   - Applications (web apps, CLIs, services)
#   - Team projects (everyone gets same versions)
#   - Personal multi-machine projects (consistency)
#
# IGNORE lock files for:
#   - Libraries (let consumers choose versions)
#   - Experimental/prototype projects
#   - Solo projects where you want flexibility
#
# Uncomment the lock file(s) for your stack:

# JavaScript / TypeScript / Bun
!bun.lockb              # Bun (fast, modern)
# !package-lock.json    # npm
# !yarn.lock            # Yarn
# !pnpm-lock.yaml       # pnpm

# Python
# !Pipfile.lock         # Pipenv
# !poetry.lock          # Poetry
# !pdm.lock             # PDM
# requirements.txt is NOT a lock file, always commit

# Ruby
# !Gemfile.lock         # Bundler

# Rust
# !Cargo.lock           # Commit for binaries, ignore for libraries

# Go
# !go.sum               # Go modules (usually committed)

# PHP
# !composer.lock        # Composer

